english:
  title: Record of the Pavilion of Solitary Joy
  author: Nam Soo-mun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The former Regional Inspector of Xiangyang, Lord Lin, rose to prominence in his governance, his name spreading far and wide. In years past, when my late father served as magistrate of Hamjoo, Lord Lin held the position of vice-magistrate, and their friendship ran deep. Thus have I long honored him as a father. One day he spoke to me thus:

    "My family has dwelt upon the upper reaches of the Geumgang River near Gongju, at the very crossroads where Gyeongsang, Jeolla, and Chungcheong provinces meet. Here the waters converge, and we call this place Samgeori—the Meeting of Three Rivers. Some five li to the south of our home, a broken ridge of mountains runs from north to south, rising after some two li into a gentle peak. Slender bamboo and thick pines clothe it in emerald beauty, most lovely to behold. The three rivers wind and coil, snaking eastward below, and long have I wondered at this place. One day I ventured to climb its heights, and behold! To the north, Wonsu Mountain rings the view like fortress walls. To the south, Gyeryong Mountain pierces the very clouds. To east and west, the lesser peaks bow and gesture in a thousand enchanting forms, each one a marvel beyond measure. Villages and fields spread like go stones cast across the near and distant lands. Captivated by this sublime landscape, grieved that such beauty had long lain neglected, I resolved to build a modest dwelling upon the left flank of the peak, and upon it to raise this pavilion.

    "Now from this vantage, the wide sand-flats and surging waters of the river merge heaven and earth into one hue. When the wind stirs, green scales ripple across the surface; when moonlight falls, the waves turn to molten silver. The coming and going of boats and birds—all their rising and sinking—occurs beneath my very feet. The layered peaks and ridges of the mountains, their great slopes and ancient forests, stretch near into verdant fields and far into the azure sky, blending with clouds and mists that transform with dawn and dusk—all this I behold from my seat. The tillers and herders, the fishermen and woodcutters singing in call and response, the travelers and wanderers moving through the four quarters—all these too I may observe while sitting.

    "Now retired from office, with cloth cap and cane, I ascend this pavilion each day. Mind and heart alike find ease; body and world both fade away. Alone I fish in the river, alone I gather on the mountain. The spring flowers and autumn moon I alone may sing to as my joy. The strange beauty of cloud-capped peaks and the purity of snow-laden pines I alone may contemplate as my joy. All that in the transformation of things may bring delight—this alone I possess exclusively. Like a cicada shedding its grimy shell to wander free beyond all things, my spirit floats unbound. Though the four seasons change their aspect, my joy alone remains constant. Though music and song have their season, my joy alone knows no end.

    "I have presumed to borrow the two characters for 'solitary joy' from the naming of Sufei Garden, and have inscribed them upon my pavilion. This may seem presumptuous. Yet he enjoyed principle; I enjoy things. There is no contradiction in sharing the same name. I beg you to record this for me."

    I could not refuse Lord Lin with mere excuses of poor writing. Long ago, our Master Confucius said, "In drinking water and resting one's arm as pillow, joy dwells within." He praised Yanhui for not altering his contentment in a narrow alley with a meager bowl, yet he never spoke of the source of such joy. The two Chengs urged scholars to seek what Confucius and Mencius found joyful, yet they too merely pointed the way without revealing it. Now Lord Lin has found joy solitary within his pavilion and asks me to write of it. Since he names it "solitary joy," this is surely beyond the knowing of ordinary men. How much more so for me, who though I have read the words of sages, do not comprehend what "solitary" truly means? How dare I write of his pavilion?

    And yet—his words say: "He enjoyed principle; I enjoy things." I have heard it said that outside principle there is no thing, and outside things there is no principle. Thus the height and depth of heaven and earth, the flowing and stillness of mountains and rivers, the soaring of hawks and leaping of fish, the flourishing and withering of grass and wood—all that appears to eye and ear—what is it if not principle itself taking form? Through Lord Lin's joy, then, might one discover the joy-path of the sages. Is it mere scenic appreciation?

    Moreover, I observe the scholars and gentlemen of this age. Though many possess gardens and lands sufficient for self-cultivation, all are bound by the fetters of rank and reputation, rushing east and west without cessation. Some never return to their native places. Those who do often merely clutch the counting-frame, calculating grain and coin—is this not to labor the very life itself? Yet Lord Lin, whose station did not match his virtue, whose years had not yet reached their decline, was able to cast off office and worldly entanglement, to wander free in mountains and streams. Is not the name "Pavilion of Solitary Joy" most fitting?

    This pavilion shall surely stand eternal alongside the Garden of Solitary Joy at Sufei, both fair beyond doubt. Yet consider: Sima Guang bore the weight of the realm's hopes and could never idle in Luoyang. Does Lord Lin, likewise bearing his era's expectations, truly possess the leisure to long enjoy this same transcendence? As for one like myself—I occupy a seat at court to no avail, labor ceaselessly yet accomplish nothing, cannot cease my rushing about—how can I not feel shame? When shall I hang up my official cap and join Lord Lin in this pavilion, reciting the Record of the Garden of Solitary Joy and singing the verses of Su Dongpo, that I might glimpse the sublime heights of their joy?
